N2  - Reviews the book, Interracial families: Current concepts and controversies by George Yancey and Richard Lewis (2009). This small book makes several unique contributions to the study of race relations: its focus on interracial dating, the issues that the children of interracial unions face, and the examination of how race relations and interracial dating have been portrayed in the media. George Yancey has probably examined interracial dating more than other scholar today. In this book Yancy and Lewis contextualize interracial dating and marriage within fairly traditional theoretical discussions. They use several perspectives: the assimilationist perspective associated with Milton Gordon and others, Merton's perspective on exchange relationships-that interracial couples exchange the status characteristics of beauty and race, and the issues associated with the "one-drop" rule-that anyone with any African ancestry is defined as African American. In the end this book is about the emerging of groups and phenomena that will continue to reduce racism. The interesting and broader range of biracial and bi-ethnic groups we will see in the coming decades-groups that do not fit nicely in to previous racial and ethnic groupings- will continue to break down the traditional classifications or racial and ethnic groups. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
