N2  - Reviews the book, Dorm room drug dealers: Drugs and the privileges of race and class by A. Rafik Mohamed and Erik D. Fritsvold (2010). This is an exciting book in the tradition of the pioneering ethnography of upper-level drug dealers by Adler (1985). Ironically, like the police, very few scholars have focused on any other segment of drug dealing other than street dealing. In contrast to previous treatises on drug dealing (Jacobs, 1998), this one provides readers with a rare view of the largely 'invisible' drug trade involving wealthy student clientele. The book is based on 6 years of fieldwork on drug dealing that was prevalent on several college campuses in southern California. In addition to the ethnographic work, the researchers had research assistants conduct interviews with active and retired dorm room dealers (p. 9). In all, there were about 50 subjects who provide the basis of the book. And, contrary to popular media images of drug dealers, nearly all of the participants were white. Unquestionably, this book is as important as any of the books published in the last two decades on drug dealing. It provides a clear portrait as to why some groups are over represented in drug arrest figures while others are not. The book should be read widely in criminology and related social science disciplines by both students and scholars of racial/ethnic inequities in the administration of criminal justice, as well as those who blindly and naively rely on crime statistics. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
