N2  - This article discusses lessons learned from the World Psychiatric Association's Open the Doors programme. Most people believe that those with mental illnesses are incapable of holding down jobs or maintaining relationships and, at worst, are dangerous, irrational and incurable. Education and the use of surveys to track people's attitudes can be valuable components of anti-stigma work, but only as part of a slew of measures and efforts to improve the lives of patients and their families. To address the stigma of mental health in a meaningful way, strategies known to be effective should become a routine part of everyday services. These include educating health-care personnel, mediating face-to-face contact between the general public and people who have experienced mental illness, or persuading journalists to avoid certain terms when describing events relating to those with mental illness. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
