N2  - Epilepsy has received none of the media attention or resources given to other equivalent health burdens, and it remains in the shadows. Although stigma has been blamed for epilepsy's poor showing in the race for a share of the health care pie, it is also true that the general public does not recognize epilepsy as a serious problem. On May 17, Steven Schachter and Frances Jensen representing the American Epilepsy Society (AES), Susan Axelrod representing Citizens United for Epilepsy (CURE), Kimberli Meadows representing the Epilepsy Foundation (EF), Robert Fisher representing , Gary Mathern representing the International League Against Epilepsy (ILAE), and I attended a pro bono workshop in Los Angeles with Lynda Resnick, a celebrated public relations expert. A major accomplishment of the workshop was to merge the divergent goals and objectives of the representative organizations into cohesive mission statements that could be used to publicize the serious health burden represented by epilepsy, and communicate the urgent need to find more effective approaches for prevention, treatment, and cure. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
