N2  - The Toyota recall crisis of 2010 has prompted much criticism in media circles, national business forums and automotive trade publications. It is hoped that business and management researchers will take an unbiased, i.e., objective and empirical examination, on the many unique aspects of this corporate crisis. The current study focuses on three central features of the evolving Toyota recall: (a) Leadership issues, (b) Brand loyalty, and (c) Ethics and leadership. In order to gauge public attitudes about these issues, we developed a brief survey instrument and a semantic differential measure. Participants (Total =109) included 72 business college students and 37 adults from the local community. Results indicated that a majority (57%) of the sample felt that Toyota leadership's handling of the recall was somewhat disappointing or very poor. Moreover, few respondents (18%) had any confidence in the veracity of public statements from Toyota. With regard to ethics, 50% of the sample felt that Toyota's decision- making is unethical to some degree. In addition, a majority (56%) expressed little faith in Toyota's transparency during this crisis. Noteworthy, only 13% felt that Toyota would probably not regain its prominence in the auto sector. These findings were discussed in light of recent research on crisis management and perception management. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
