N2  - Reviews the book, Public Opinion and Criminal Justice edited by Jane Wood and Theresa Gannon (2009). This book accurately procures public opinion and understand its influence on criminal justice policy. In the first half of the book, the chapter authors focus on the formation and function of public opinion. In the second half of the book, the chapter authors examine specific public opinions toward victims and offenders. For instance, public attitudes and the media's overrepresentation of sensational crimes have influenced the way rape and other victims of violence interact with the criminal justice system, by affecting the victims' reluctance to report, how the cases are prosecuted, and how the victims are treated. The main limitation of the book is a subtle incompatibility among the chapters. The book also leaves the reader questioning why public opinion receives attention. However, one of the biggest strength of the book is its attention to rape myths, sexual offenders, and mentally ill offenders as examples of situations when attempting to change public opinion is arguably better than changing the law. Hence, the editors have collected a series of chapters that would be useful reading for graduate students in political science, criminology, criminal justice, and forensic psychology. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
