N2  - Reviews the book Beyond common sense: Psychological science in the courtroom edited by Eugene Borgida and Susan T. Fiske (see record 2007-09185-000). In this book, noted social psychologists Borgida and Fiske have collected 21 essays on a variety of legal issues on which social psychology has conducted research and therefore has something to say. The topics considered range widely, and include prejudice and discrimination, sexual harassment, eyewitness identification, repressed and recovered memory, confessions, polygraph testing, death penalty laws, pretrial publicity, and media violence. The last portion of the book directly links the issue of technology transfer to the legal system. Many issues are debated, such as the problem of reasoning from the general to the specific-whether experts may use general observations from research to opine about a specific case. The authors as a group are clearly two-sided, with some arguing the ease of using social scientific findings to shape legal policy, and others being more skeptical. Thus, whatever one's position about the value of common sense, this book will be recognized as a major contribution to contemporary debates on the role of science in policy making. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
