N2  - Social identity theory was applied to examine Muslim (n = 87) and Westerner (n = 119) attitudes toward forgiveness and reconciliation in the context of terrorism in a 2 (Salient Identity: Muslim, Westerner) x2 (Ingroup Identity: social, human) quasi-experimental design. Priming terrorism at the inclusive, human level encourages greater forgiveness and reconciliation than at the social level of group identity. Muslims tended to be more forgiving and conciliatory in the human condition, but tended to be less forgiving than Westerners in the social condition. Overall, priming affected Muslim attitudes but not Westerner attitudes. Finally, forgiveness mediated between ingroup identity and reconciliation. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
